  <section id="how-we-evaluate">
    <h2>How we evaluate</h2>
    <p>We researched each model using current Amazon listings, manufacturer documentation, and repeat buyer feedback patterns focused on espresso workflow. Instead of judging grinders by marketing language, we prioritized practical signals: click precision, burr alignment stability, dose-to-dose consistency, grind speed for an 18g espresso dose, and cleanup burden over a normal week of use.</p>
    <p>Espresso under $100 requires compromise, so our rankings weight compromise quality rather than chasing unrealistic perfection. For example, a grinder can score well here even if it is not a true specialty benchmark, as long as it gives dependable control for the price and does not force constant redialing after minor bean changes. We also separate pressurized-basket viability from non-pressurized-basket viability, because those are very different standards in real kitchens.</p>
    <p>Finally, we compare total daily friction, not only cup quality. If a grinder creates excessive static mess, takes too long to grind dense beans, or needs fiddly disassembly every few days, it falls in rank even when the burr set is decent. People shopping this budget tier usually want predictable mornings, not a technical side project before coffee.</p>
